 for bestpractices and # Subscription Management

## Overview
This prompt guides the AI development tool to implement a robust Subscription Management feature for QuestHabit. The system must enable users to view and modify subscription plans, manage billing methods, and handle proration, cancellations, and reactivations. It must integrate with Stripe for payments, provide secure endpoints, maintain an audit trail, and expose two pages: Order / Transaction History and Subscription Management. All code must be guarded against null/undefined values before using array methods, initialize arrays with correct useState defaults, and consistently apply the runtime-safety rules described in the project’s mandatory coding standards.

## Components to Build
- Subscription Management Page (page_billing_subscription)
  - Plan picker with real-time proration preview and upgrade/downgrade flow
  - Billing method management (add/update/delete payment methods via Stripe)
  - Cancel plan with retention messaging and reactivation workflow
  - View upcoming invoice, next bill date, and usage/proration details
  - Re-authentication prompt for billing-sensitive actions
  - Audit trail entries for each operation (plan change, cancellation, billing method updates)
- Order / Transaction History Page (page_billing_history)
  - List of invoices and receipts
  - Download invoices/receipts (PDF or CSV)
  - Billing details summary per transaction
  - Filters by date range, plan, and status
  - Null-safe rendering and empty-state messaging
- Backend Stripe Integration
  - Create/Update/Cancel subscriptions
  - Manage payment methods (setup intent, attach/detach payment methods)
  - Retrieve invoices and upcoming invoices
  - Webhook listeners for Stripe events (invoice.paid, subscription.updated, payment_method.attached, customer.subscription.deleted, etc.)
  - Proration handling and invoice preview calculations
- Data Layer
  - User, Subscription, BillingMethod, Invoice, AuditLog models
  - Secure association between user and subscription
  - Audit trails with actor, action, timestamp, and payload
- API Layer
  - REST/GraphQL endpoints to fetch subscription state, update plans, manage billing methods, cancel/reactivate, fetch invoices, and download assets
  - Input validation and strict error handling

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks/Libraries: React (with TypeScript), React Query or SWR for data fetching, Zustand/Redux/MReact Context for global auth state, and Stripe.js for client-side operations.
- UI Components:
  - PlanCard: shows plan name, price, features, and status; supports selection.
  - BillingMethodCard: displays current payment method with options to edit/remove; integrate Stripe Payment Method UI.
  - UpcomingInvoicePanel: shows next invoice date, amount, prorations, and estimated total after plan change.
  - ProrationPreview: real-time calculation when selecting a new plan.
  - CancelationBanner: retention messaging with option to keep account active, and reroute to reactivation if canceled.
  - ReauthModal: require re-authentication for billing-sensitive actions.
  - InvoiceList: for history page, with download actions and billing details.
  - DownloadButton: triggers secure asset generation (PDF/CSV) via backend.
- Data Handling:
  - Use data ?? [] when mapping lists from API responses.
  - Guard all array method calls with Array.isArray checks or (data ?? []).map(...).
  - Initialize state with proper defaults: useState<BillingMethod[]>([]) and useState<Invoice[]>([]).
  - Validate API responses: const subs = Array.isArray(response?.data?.subscription) ? response.data.subscription : null; and fallback to safe defaults.
- Interactions:
  - Plan change flow should trigger Stripe proration calculation on the client preview and then confirm on server.
  - Payment method updates via Stripe Elements/Stripe SDK with proper error handling and UI feedback.
  - Cancellations should reflect a retention window and trigger reactivation path.
  - All sensitive actions require re-authentication modal.
- Security:
  - Token-based authentication (JWT/OAuth) with re-auth checks for billing changes.
  - CSRF protection for state-changing endpoints.
  - Ensure client never exposes Stripe private keys; only publishable keys on the frontend.
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigable controls, ARIA labels, and color contrast per design system.

### Backend
- Language/Stack: Node.js/Express or equivalent, TypeScript preferred, Prisma or Sequelize ORM, PostgreSQL database.
- API Endpoints:
  - GET /api/subscriptions/:userId -> fetch current subscription state
  - POST /api/subscriptions/change-plan -> change plan with selected planId; returns proration preview
  - POST /api/subscriptions/cancel -> initiate cancellation with retention policy
  - POST /api/subscriptions/reactivate -> reactivate subscription
  - POST /api/billing/methods -> add/update/delete payment methods via Stripe
  - GET /api/invoices -> list invoices for a user
  - GET /api/invoices/:invoiceId/download -> download invoice/receipt
  - GET /api/audit-logs -> fetch audit trail
  - Stripe Webhooks endpoint to process events
- Data Models (simplified schema):
  - User { id, email, ... }
  - Subscription { id, userId, stripeSubscriptionId, planId, status, currentPeriodStart, currentPeriodEnd, nextInvoiceDate, quantity, prorationPurchaseItem, cancelAtPeriodEnd? }
  - Plan { id, name, stripePlanId, price, interval, features[] }
  - BillingMethod { id, userId, stripePaymentMethodId, brand, last4, expMonth, expYear, isDefault }
  - Invoice { id, userId, stripeInvoiceId, amountDue, currency, status, periodStart, periodEnd, pdfUrl, receiptUrl }
  - AuditLog { id, userId, actorId, action, targetId, payload, timestamp }
- Stripe Integration:
  - Use Stripe API to create/update subscriptions, attach/detach payment methods, retrieve upcoming invoices
  - Implement prorations handling, invoice previews via Stripe.invoice.upcoming or similar
  - Webhooks to update local DB and trigger notifications
- Security:
  - Validate user tokens, enforce authorization for each operation
  - Sanitize all inputs, guard against SQL/NoSQL injections
- Validation:
  - Ensure plan changes only to active plans; check that user has a valid payment method
  - Ensure cancellation windows respect policy
  - Validate invoice/download actions only for authorized users
- Database Migrations:
  - Create tables for subscriptions, billing_methods, invoices, plans, and audit_logs
  - Create indices on userId, stripe IDs, and status for performance

### Integration
- Data Flow:
  - Frontend calls API to fetch current subscription and invoices; backend fetches Stripe data and stores necessary state
  - On plan change: client shows proration preview; server confirms, updates Stripe subscription, then updates local DB and emits an event to frontend
  - On cancellation: server marks cancellation date; Stripe subscription cancels at period end; frontend shows retention messaging
  - Billing method changes propagate to Stripe; card updates reflect in upcoming invoices
  - Invoices fetched from Stripe and cached in DB; downloadable PDFs/receipts served by backend
- State Management:
  - Centralized subscription state (current plan, status, next invoice date, payment methods)
  - Audit trail updates on every billing-related operation
- Error Handling:
  - Unified error responses with code, message, and remediation steps
  - Retry logic for transient Stripe/network errors
- Testing:
  - Unit tests for data transformation and validation
  - Integration tests for Stripe webhooks
  - E2E tests for end-to-end flows: view subscription, change plan, update payment method, cancel/reactivate, download invoice

## User Experience Flow
1. User signs in and navigates to Subscription Management (page_billing_subscription)
2. Dashboard shows current plan, next invoice date, and upcoming proration preview if changing plans
3. User selects a new plan:
   - Client shows proration preview (amount, period change)
   - User confirms; frontend calls API to apply plan change
   - Backend validates, creates/updates Stripe subscription, stores new state, computes proration
   - On success, UI confirms update with celebratory micro-interactions; audit log entry created
4. User manages Billing Methods:
   - User adds/updates a payment method via Stripe UI
   - Backend ties payment method to Stripe customer and updates default method
   - Upcoming invoices reflect the new method; success toast shown
5. User Cancels Subscription:
   - Cancellation message explains retention window and impact
   - If user confirms, server sets cancellation at period end, updates Stripe subscription, stores state
   - User can reactivate before end of period; reactivation flow resumes standard billing
6. User views Upcoming Invoices:
   - See next bill date and estimated amount; as plan changes occur, preview shows adjusted amounts
7. User Navigates to Order / Transaction History (page_billing_history)
   - See list of invoices and receipts; download options available
   - Billing details per transaction; status filters
8. Security:
   - For any billing changes, a re-authentication modal prompts the user to re-enter credentials
   - All operations produce audit trail entries
9. Webhooks:
   - Stripe events update subscriptions, invoices, and payment methods; frontend may show real-time updates via polling or websocket

